<Review>I just like waiting for a train here. The station architecture and the aesthetics of it all just makes me feel at ease for some reason. This station is an ideal location for the opening or end credits of a romantic comedy or drama. If you're ever passing by, don't hesitate to park your car and catch the train towards downtown LA or San Diego. You'll enjoy waiting here, at least I know I do.<//Review>< Pics>

< text>
Trains from into union station are often late here. There is a repetitive announcement on an intercom to let you know every 5 minutes. That's  great but the sometimes muffled and unclear. Also, tapping on google mas gives you a schedule right away which is nice so you dont have to download the app, but it's not usually up to date with delays. The lobby smells like the 1960's bars of asbestos and cigarettes</text>

<Time>1346799511553< /Time><Review>In general, I love taking the train. The food car, the scenery, and the slowed down pace you experience. However, I recommend avoiding any segments of travel by Amtrak buses. I was a bit leery of it, but the agent on the phone said "Oh they are not like greyhound or anything, these are Amtrak buses, very nice." Uh, not really. We left Santa Ana at midnight, or were supposed to. The driver was about 20 minutes late, no big deal I guess, my sister was waiting with my son and I for the train to arrive..and even tho Santa Ana is not the first place I would choose to be around midnite..nothing happened. The problem was after we got on..the bus driver got lost, and there we were, not on a free way or main thoroughfare, but lost, in a "bad" part of Santa Ana. Me and my son..and a few rough looking guys saying they hoped the bus didnt get 'jacked'. The driver announced over the PA system if anyone was familiar with the area and if so could they give him directions.. Fortunately, someone did, and after about 15 -30 minutes, we got back on track. Every segment of our 3 leg trip was late, which I personally do not mind much. However I DO mind being put in danger. When I finally got through to Customer Relations after getting home and spoke with Angela, she said there was no record of the driver getting lost or being late (after about 25 minutes on the phone with her looking through her different "screens'" and explaining that the buses are leased and difficult to get information on. She asked for the bus driver's name, saying they don't even know that.) She actually said the bus arrived early, and there was nothing she could do. I may take the train again, as I have had other good experiences with train only trips, but my recommendation is stay away from the buses. And if anything goes wrong, I would get names and make sure the employees report the problem, be it lateness, getting lost or what have you.< /Review><Pics>None</Pics>< user_name>

< Review>
This is my favorite japanese style crepe place. I have been coming here for years and it never disappoints. First time was in 2011.

Toppings and ingredients are always fresh. The creeper batter is always amazing, lots of flavor and the right amount of chewiness to lightness.

Prices can get high if you build your own crepe, but the location is in Beverly Hills..

I always get the Nutty Banana with earl grey crepe but they no longer have the earl grey. A little disappointing but they have other great choices.

Staff is friendly, and the place is quite small. So, if you catch it at a busy time, it's tough to move around.</Review>

<user>117670738005223003306< /user>< Text>
I had a Harajuku Crepe in Japan and this place in Beverly Hills tasted better!! :) I'm impressed! :D

This is a cute little cafe in Beverly Hills. There are about 2 small tables and a couch for seating. The guy who makes the crepes is Japanese and is really nice!

If you're here, you gotta try a crepe. You can also order boba or tea too. How it works is that you get to customize your crepe by which type of crepe you want, fruits, toppings, fillings, and/or ice cream. And with each thing you choose, there's a cost.

What I got:
-Earl grey crepe $3
-Strawberries $1
-Whipped cream $0.50
-Nutella $0.50
-Green tea ice cream $0.50

Total: $6 (Totally worth it!!)

The crepe was thin and perfectly cooked! Everything was well-portioned and wasn't too sweet.

Only downside is the parking. You gotta try to find a meter or park in one of the public lots/garages.

Overall, I am a fan and will definitely be back! A great place for dessert!< /Text>

This place is so damn good!

I've been wanting to try this place for the longest! We had dinner on the Westside and decided to save room to try Harajuku Crepe for dessert.

We shared an original crepe filled with fresh strawberries, green tea ice cream, and nutella. It was so good that sharing was hard. I wanted it all to myself!

Finding this place was a tad frustrating. It was nighttime so it was dark and hard to see the sign. We kept missing it! JFYI, it's located right next to Vidal Sassoon. Parking sucks too! BUT you can park at the Beverly Gardens. It's metered parking and free after 8PM.<//Review>

< rating>
3</rating>
< Review>
Don't really understand what the hype is around Harajuku Crepes. Came here on a Saturday 15 minutes before closing and was amazed by how affordable these crepes are, and the option of choosing sesame and earl grey crepe batter. But after asking the cashier, I decided to stick with the original batter, since it was most popular. Included in the crepe, I had banana, sheet of mochi, nutella, and almonds (they ran out of whipped cream). The crepe itself was $3, and the toppings ranged form $0.25 - $1. Mine came out to be $6-7.

When I received my crepe, I noticed how small it was and how little toppings it came with... No wonder why it was so cheap! Secondly, just from holding the crepe, I already knew it wouldn't be good (or as good as other crepes I've had), because it wasn't the crispy crepe. It was really soft, like a pancake, which I'm not really a fan of.

It wasn't a "bad" crepe per se, but just not my cup of tea. I probably wouldn't come back...< /Review>

<Text>I came here with a group of 9 on a Friday night. I got a matcha crepe with vanilla ice cream, whipped cream, and mochi. It came out to be $6. The crepe was rather smaller than other places, but still pretty good. The mochi was wrapped within the edges of the crepe, allowing me to eat ice cream and mochi in every bite.

One downside is that the place is rather small, so there wasn't much seating and we ended up standing outside to eat the crepes. In addition, waiting for the crepes took a while, especially considering the size of the crepes and the lack of customers while we were there.

Parking is also hard to find. Had to park near a park a block away.

Overall, not a bad crepe place, but definitely have had better with faster service.

Note: There is a minimum credit card charge of $6.< /Text><pics>None<//pics><response>None< /response>< Gmap_id>

<Name>Yvette Tung<//Name><Gmap_id>0x80c2bc07b2c9f26d:0x3f4e2e42f2b07520<//Gmap_id><Pics>None</Pics><review>Harajuku Crepe is a fantastic place to take a break from all the Rodeo Drive window shopping ;) Crepes here are A-MA-ZING!

The owner developed his skills at a creperie in Japan, and invented his own recipe for this venture. The not-so-secret ingredient that makes the crepes here extra special is MOCHI powder! It makes the crepe itself slightly thicker than French style crepes while still maintaining the fluffy softness we looove.

What's also great is the selection of flavors--original, green tea, earl grey and buckwheat (yes, buckwheat!)--ensures that you're never going to get bored of the menu. Since they're very generous with their toppings, the finished crepes are often monstrous.

Finally, a worthy successor to the now defunct crepe nazi on Sawtelle!</review>< Response>

<Gmap_id>0x808f9dd90268c879:0xf954be96b03a60c0<//Gmap_id><review>Many groups share the facilities here. in the parking lot is relatively small given the size of the facility. If a large group has arrived first, then you may need to park a block or two away from the facility, given that street parking is of course taken up by people who live in the neighborhood.

They've completely redone the athletic fields, replacing them all with artificial turf. It appears that a really nice job was done.

The complication is that the turf has been constructed with an infill product that appears to be different than cork or rubber -- possibly something like ground up nutshells or something similar.
In my first game as a coach at the facility, eight players across the two soccer teams ended up with abrasions on their hips, elbows, and forearms after they fell and scraped themselves on the ground. Think something akin to rug burns. I've played and coached on multiple other artificial turf fields, and never seen more than two or three scrapes like this over an entire season.
If you're a coach of teams that will play on this field, definitely bring the extra large size bandages with you to your games.< /review><username>Donald Nagle< /username><response>None<//response></record>

<user>104971529801401968729</user>< user_name>

<Time>1623872057058</Time>< rate>

< review>
Looked this spot up before coming to Pismo for a staycation and glad I did. There's a plethora of spots in downtown Pismo by the pier that...aren't...incredibly...........diverse....in their offerings. Everyone has sides, burgers, boozy beverages, and their own version of clam chowder but Moreno's has incredibly flavorful Mexican fare, GREAT service, and a simple menu that's not trying to be more than what it is supposed to be.
I had a shrimp quesadilla; my wife had a breakfast burrito, and both were devoured within minutes of receiving them.
I needed more and ordered a barbacoa taco and an asada taco...both delicious and washed down with a Jarritos.
Clean joint with great food and friendly service.....what more does anyone need? Definitely returning the next time we are in town.</review>

< Text>
I am a north bay lady and my husband and I realized we should get some tacos since we were south.  These tacos reminded me how special a simple taco can be!  The meat is showcased and Morenos does a fantastic job at their meats.  I will definitely be hitting this place up again before we leave.  It is clearly a true family business.   The momma was so friendly and appreciative of how much we loved their food.  The kind of place you want to support!  If I lived in PB, I know I would be here many times a week!< /Text>

< Review>
Moreno's taqueria is a new spot in Pismo Beach, but they are not new to the industry and it shows! They were very polite and greeting as we entered and were Covid friendly. We ordered several of their tacos (carnitas, al pastor, chile verde, chicken, and carne asada). They offer a red and green salsa depending on your liking and the tacos are served with a generous amount of lemon. We rode our bikes in from Oceano and brought some 805 cerveza with us as a beach dinner date. We'll definitely be back.</Review>

I have eaten burritos and tacos from all over the United States. However, Moreno's Taqueria  had the best breakfast burrito, burrito, taco, and quesadillas without any real competition. The welcoming nature of this small taqueria is representative of how much care and love they put behind each item they prepare for you.

If the food wasn't enough, the employees make you want to come back on a regular basis. I visited Pismo beach for 1 week, and I made it a point to visit them at least once a day. I loved everything they served me, and the conversations they had with me and my wife. I can't wait to come back!< /Text>

< review>
No frills Filipino takeout spot!

Starting with the con: I came in on a Sunday and they claimed they couldn‚Äôt take cash, despite the multiple CC stickers on the door (they even have an Apple Pay sticker!) Okay, fine - I drove down the street to an ATM to get cash.

Pros: the food was great, almost as good as my mom‚Äôs. The pork sinigang was amazing, broth was perfect and the meat had the perfect amount of fat and was melt in your mouth. My husband liked the BBQ skewers. The tray of lumpia shanghai we ordered for a dinner party was a hit - the best we‚Äôve had since moving to LA probably because unlike other places, it didn‚Äôt taste freezer burnt.

Looking forward to trying more of their ulam when I‚Äôm feeling homesick.< /review>

< Text>
I lived in the Cannon Management owned Temecula Creek Villa Apartments for a total of 13 months, and while the move in process was easy, the apartments themselves are well laid out, and the rent is affordable- They're clearly out to make their money in deposits.

Upon move out we were sent an invoice for $1,129.05 and this includes a $65 credit for overpaying our rent! I called Cannon Management and was referred to Mike Vandaele, who oversees Temecula Creek Villas.

He was so incredibly rude, it was mind blowing.

When I told him there was a $500 pet deposit unaccounted for he told me that it was on me to prove that it had been paid- no offer to look in to it or anything. And no surprise, but also no apology after I provided the proof.

When I asked for receipts of the renovations paid for- the painting, the steam cleaning, etc. He told me they were not required to provide them (which they are).

When I explained that per California civil code 1950.5   "A landlord cannot routinely charge each tenant for cleaning carpets, drapes, walls, or windows in order to prepare the rental unit for the next tenancy."  and also, Brown, Warner and Portman, The California Landlord‚Äôs Law Book, Vol. I: Rights & Responsibilities determined that minor marks or nicks in the walls are the landlord's responsibility as they fall under "general wear and tear". He blew me off and refused to discuss the charges. I believe his exact words were "We're done here".

He's been rude, uncooperative, and unwilling to explain or provide proof for any of the charges.

Here's what they charged for-

$144.70 (Prorated) for "Paint Touch Ups"
$135 to clean the unit
$83.13 (prorated) to steam clean the tile
$831.79 (prorated) to replace the carpet

Replacing the carpet I'm fine with- we got a puppy, I get it- but then charging us a $135 cleaning charge WHICH INCLUDES VACUUMING THE CARPETS is ridiculous. On top of that they also charged $83 to "steam clean the tile" when "mop floors" is also included in that $135 cleaning fee. When I pointed this out, Mr. Vandaele offered a $5 credit "because that's about all it's worth".

After reading all the other reviews and similar stories from other former tenants- I will never consider renting from a Cannon Management owned property ever again, and I will be sure to suggest the same to my friends and family.<//Text>

<Text>Although we did not stay on The RUBA, we were just a short 2 mile walk away over the mountain at Bicycle Lake. The name is a little deceiving with the complete absence of water or bicycles, but the heat waves coming off of the ground made it easy to imagine a luscious oasis. The RUBA is a traveler‚Äôs delight with long walks, few trees to block the view, and a plethora of restaurants to satisfy your every craving. However, if you do not want to be shackled by the pampered accommodations of RUBA, I would highly recommend the quick trip to Bicycle Lake. Get back to your pioneer roots with no showers or indoor plumbing. I will definitely come back for years to come.</Text>< Pictures>

<user_id>111869359263814383177< /user_id>< review>
I have to say I definitely concur with everyone else. The RUBA is a fantastic getaway when you're trying to leave the life of modern conveniences behind you. The beauty of nature can be seen when someone throws trash on the ground and it is instantly picked up by a flock of crows. As you walk around on the "soft" sand you can listen to the crows quietly chirping in the background.

If shopping is your game, head on down to the Base Supply Center where everything is conveniently priced and never out of stock. Don't forget to grab some free popcorn on your way out, the slushy machine is broken.

Finally, if you enjoy fine dining and fanciful delicacies, head on down to the strip where you can enjoy such fine establishments as Pizza Hut, Taco Bell, and Subway.

I am sure to visit again! CANNOT WAIT!</review>

<user_name>Abel Uribe</user_name><Response>None</Response><UserId.>103906027254054254866</UserId.><rating>5</rating>< review>
This fine resort is located in beautiful southern California where you can soak up enough sun to burn your skin and sand to enter every crevice of anything you own (even that place, don't like you don't know). Ruba resort come equipped with "Alcatraz" style showers (drop your soap and shower is over), great stand in dinning experience with limited walking space, best of all the toilet rooms come equipped with shower curtains that are already falling apart and as bonus you're lucky if half your body doesn't stick out. The sleeping accommodations are great if you like company (up to 144 persons per room). So if you're near the Barstow area and looking for a life get away, this is the place to be.< /review>

< Text>
This is definitely one of my favorite vacation hotspots. The facilities are accommodating in the temperate and breathtaking landscape. The ruba offers a wide variety of foods that can satisfy any pallet. Feeling adventurous? Be sure to try the exhilarating hike through the motorpool, taking in all the sights, sounds, and fresh air of the beautiful scenery. Much like other 5 star resorts, it can get a little bit crowded during the tourist season. Be sure to reserve your spot as soon as you can!<//Text>

<Text>Nestled in a cozy corner of this quaint little desert community you will find this hidden gem.  Spacious living areas and unique bath house style bathing  creates an upper class feel matched only by lavish Dubai living.  Take a midnight stroll through the "Goodyear filtered" sands of the automotive garden on your way to your very own observation tower. There you will spend what's seems like a lifetime enjoying the views of the surrounding rolling convoy dust clouds filling the sky.  Lazer tag anyone? This place has a multitude of outdoor activities. Mtn hiking, cave exploring,  many dry lakebeds that you can look at but never touch and let's not forget tortoise dodging!  Love this place? You should check out another hotspot just down the road. Book your trip to Yermo  CA and never miss the exciting action of the US railroad service!</Text><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNNuE16eD3G2N8s4jKv_Mw9Fc4AsOmftYxeD6ig=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pictures>< Rate>

<text>Arrived on one of the fanciest charter buses with all the bells and whistles after a relaxing 15 hour bus ride. As I stepped off of the bus at 0430 in the morning into a cool 100 degrees, I could tell this was going to be paradise. As I settled into my cottage, which was insulated with tan flex seal and boasted a comforting open floor plan, I took in the full aroma of axe spray and scrotum. Exploring the resort brought many adventures. One of my favorite things to do was wait in line to get a basket pass to the shoppette. By the time i made it to the register to pay for my 69 cent slushy, it was already devoured, but the customer service was second to none, so i never minded paying for an empty cup. The basket nazis were also friendly. It didn't matter how tired I was, I always had plenty of energy to enjoy the scenery at connex yard. My favorite part of the safari, called the box, was putting on mopp gear, as the desert nights in August can drop to a chilly 98 degrees. I also enjoyed socializing with the local populace and did not mind the risk of contracting notional congo fever. Our tour guides, the OCs, we're very friendly and offered constructive criticism such as "you are the worst group ever". If you were lucky enough to step away from the ruba resort, which was frowned upon, you might have had the opportunity to enjoy other sites such as wild donkeys crapping in the family park or perhaps catch a glimpse of the $50,000 tortoise. If you were willing to chance an article 15 to work off your 8 dollar burrito and walk to the gym, which is not open to rotational units, you would have a fitness experience only comparable to 5 star hotels...so I've been told. My only criticism was that, while having a bowel movement, the 13 pieces of old tape stuck to the shower curtain door did not allow for the breathtaking open view of the clogged urine troughs I was hoping for. It just wasn't the same feeling as taking a dump out in the open desert with no cover in front of the luring eyes of our tour guides into a plastic bag, then carrying said bag back through a group of your friends, putting it in a clear trash bag, because smelling it cooking in the heat all day did not stimulate the senses enough. There's always next year.<//text><Gmap_id>0x80c438e5f3a22f97:0x21a2f859d551567b</Gmap_id>< user_name>
J O</user_name>

<UserId.>116006376588231761277</UserId.>< text>
At first I thought the accommodations at the RUBA were going to be crappy tin buildings, boy was I wrong. They really turned up their game on the tin roof, concrete floor 5 million man barracks buy using spray foam for walls. It's much softer than metal and just as hot when the air conditioning constantly breaks.

I particularly enjoyed urinating in troughs that were level so that when you flushed them the water just diluted it and not drain. This in turn created a wonderful aroma of dead animals and death. The glorious stench was only enhanced by the toilets which were backed up most of the days with turds the size of forest trees and monuments of wet wipes waving to you from above the water line.

But everything cannot be perfect which is why I'm only giving the RUBA four stars and not five. I was not impressed by the medical care at all. When you show up each morning and night you only get to see a PA, I mean they're not even doctors. When they ONLY gave me a shot of toradol, muscle relaxers and other NSAIDS for my back pain, for the 20th time, I immediately asked for an MRI which was denied. Knowing better than the PA's my wife deduced (researched WebMD) that I needed surgery for my chronic low back pain. My debilitating pain is mainly exacerbated any time my team leader asks me to work. My wife also told me to try lavender oil. I did what she said, because I have no spine or thoughts of my own, and it not only helped my anxiety from being yelled at by NCO's but decreased by body odor caused by Sun constantly beating down upon my lowbrow which causes me to perspire. I think they should hire my wife to work there, she can search google as good as any PA.

All in all if you like extremely overpriced & poor quality food trucks, hour long lines in the 100+ degree weather, and lots of smelly people having coitus in the Porta Potty and containers at night, then you've found your paradise. If that's not your thing, which I cannot understand, you just might be normal.</text>

< Text>
Luxuy lodging, exquisite eating, exotic flora & fauna, breathtaking views, amazing night time views of the sky... what's not to love. I remember the feel of Saran Wrap peeling apart from my thighs as the package I had stowed between my legs shifted in my rush to be the last off the 5 star bus. I squinted my eyes to the blinding beauty that is he RUBA, licked my lips, and could swear I tasted the local layer of powdered/confectioners dust settling on my now moistened but cracked lips. A hint of dried urine was suspected as the filler ingredient. The hardships brought me closer to my brethren as the cosy Quarters allowed us to exchange the scents of musk de toilette, and second hand or partially deoxygenated air. I did however appreciate the morning greeting of bumping elbows with strangers while trying to shower. Such good mannered folks. Some toilet stalls were occupied by my fellows, or the occasional Turd who weighs an average of 12.5 Courics (to big to fight with and takes too long to evacuate the stall). Some of the locals looked suspiciously like giant crows and I am sure their size is attributed to the leftovers that our resort donates to them. Deeeeelish', by the way. Mystery meats, preserved fresh fruits, compacted eggs, sugar flavored with fruit juices.... ohhhh I can't do this to myself right now!!! You can even pet the occasional rats whose features resemble that of Mr Splinter. I remember the night sky, dust brown and slightly reminiscent of a cool sand blaster. Just gorgeous. 5/5 would recommend that you do not miss the chance to come here. Overall the accommodations were out of this world.< /Text>

<Time>1428515305173</Time><Rating>5</Rating>< Text>
Agree with the above review. The rent is free here! I couldn't believe it. Although the bathrooms are actually located outside of the living space, it's worth the short (or long) walk, depending on where they place you. A lot of trash is always blowing around, but that's OK because there are constantly roaming groups of people volunteering to pick it all up! My entire face has peeled off three times while here, but man you should see my tan. There is local shopping and eateries on wheels that charge a substantial fee for their meals, but it is somewhat better than the free food that is offered at the standing-room only establishments spread across Ruba. Don't venture too far off Ruba without your proper safety gear or you will be confronted and yelled at by random strangers. After one week, you get to go on a special trip and camp out under the stars in the Mojave desert for two whole weeks. Sadly they didn't tell us there would be no shower facilities while we were out there. They told us we couldn't take phones, but I swear I heard people talking in the porta-potties out there. This is my second time visiting and I have to say, this place gets better with every visit.<//Text>

5<//Rating>
< text>
A little slice of heaven in the California desert, the RUBA truly is an oasis for those travelers seeking tranquility and senic bliss.  Let the perfectly manicured and lush green grass flooring of the rooms massage your tired feet at the end of a long day as the melodic beats of helicopter rotor blades lull you into an unbelievably peaceful slumber. Travelers will enjoy this "blast from the past" with rocky brown sandy terrain that stretches for miles and puts you back in time with your ancestors from long ago.

The cuisine is phenomenal with a myriad of options day or night.  No need for room service when the food trucks are constantly on patrol for hungry guests, spreading their infectious Home Depot day worker charm to all those who choose to partake.  Looking for dessert?  The shoppette is conveniently located just a minutes walk from any one of the bungalows.  In the mood for something sweeter? What could be sweeter than the shaved ice truck that appears randomly to deliver fresh snow cones... and, of course, smiles.

The feeling of isolation gives way after a few short days to make way for true zen.  Travelers will find themselves completely in harmony with the natural landscape, covered in the dust of self satisfaction, helping you further connect to your surroundings.  You will never find yourself bored as the daily tasks are plentiful and, and while completely meaningless and mundane, always ensure you are greeted by that feeling of accomplishment as you lay down to rest and stare up at the stars.

Will definetly stay here in the future.  A total steal for those traveling on a budget.  An absolute gem!< /text>

<review>Finally!!!!
Halal Vietnamese food and it is awesome.
We called them 30mins before closing, if we can still come, very politely they told us to come.
People there were very humble, as a it was my first time in a Vietnamese restaurant, they explained me the items in their menu.
We ordered Champa chicken, Bo and Bun Bo.

This was the best chicken I ever had, I loved it. It's kinda crispy chicken  cooked with lemongrass.

Both the soups were tasty and the beef was perfect cooked.
I liked Bo more then Bun Bo.
Bun Bo had  something like chunks of fat in it that I didn't like that much.
Bo was the best!!!!
I will highly recommend this place and I will visit this again.</review>< pictures>

< date>
1584321115663<//date>
<Rating>5< /Rating><review>This restaurant has a unique offer which is halal Vietnamese cuisine prepared by a minority Muslims community in Vietnam called Champa. The menu is small but they use the best fresh ingredients and execution of each dish is authentic. I have lived in south east Asia 25 years and I can say with certainty they prepare dishes with authentic recipe. The staff are extremely polite and well mannered. The dishes to must try is the beef stew with french baguette, very uniquely vietnamese. I learned of this dish when Anthony Bourdain visited vietnam in his show. A French vietnamese fusion dish. I have been to about six different vietnamese restaurant in bay area and 5 in Canada never seen this beef stew on the menu.  The mango salad is fresh, herbatious, sour, slightly spicy, nutty and sweet all same time. I have tried the chicken pho which is very subtle but good quality organic chicken. I most of the times eat the spicy beef pho and I always ask for extra spicy chilly paste or sate. Truly unique experience is also their curry which is unique to their region. To me it's very similar to Thai muslim or malay style coconut curry type broth. If you like malay style or even Burmese Muslim style curry you will like the Champa curry. I have tried their fried wings simple, good quality fresh chicken and simple seasoning of salty, sour and sweet glaze typical of South East Asia cuisine balance of these flavors together.  I have visited this restaurant five times with a gap of one month each time. Every time they delivered the end product with the same excellent quality. This is a relatively new restaurant one year or so. I wish them lots of success in the future. I hope others come to this wonderful restaurant to experience the unique cuisine of champa. We need more places like Champa that bring unique cuisine from minority community all across the globe. A must place to try.< /review><pictures>None<//pictures><Response>None<//Response>< gmapID>

Enjoyed the Chicken Vermicelli Bowl (b√∫n g√†), served boneless and skinless, with fish sauce on the side. Chicken pieces cut just right, very tender, interesting spices, just the way I like it. <rating>5< /rating><Review>Wow Wow Wow!!!  You have to go see a movie here!!!!  Absolutely gorgeous theatre remodeled art deco, a throwback to yesteryear and a fun place to hangout.  You can order your dinner, drinks at the Alameda Cinema Grill, they'll deliver right to your chair.   Get there a little early, eat your dinner, sip a glass of Cabernet, watch a great movie, so much fun.  Take in the amazing architecture and the inspiring detail that makes this historic treasure so worth visiting.  The Alameda Theatre is an Art Deco movie theatre built in 1932, designed by renowned architect Timothy L. Pflueger and was the last grand movie palace built in the San Francisco Bay Area.  Highly recommend!</Review>< pictures>

<gmap_id>0x808f86be0f8c89dd:0x7b58c36ce6683445</gmap_id><user_name>Sister Regena Ross</user_name><Time>1558161101371</Time>< Text>
I really enjoyed my visit to this theater.  I usually only go for Warriors watch parties ($5).  The theater is so clean and the employees are friendly.  The environment is peaceful until people like me become rowdy during the game.  I have a lot of fun with the other WARRIORS fans.  We give Hi-5s and cheer "Waaaaaariars, Waaaaaariars" and "DEFENSE, DEFENSE!" You can even have food delivered from the restaurant next door to your seat if you are sitting in the reserved section and delivered to the theater door if sitting in the general section.  I can watch the game at home but I really like the large screen and the people.  It is the next best thing to being at the Coliseum.  I will definitely will go back to the Alameda Theater for other games and movies on a discount day.<//Text>

<name>Beatriz<//name>< Time>
1559667240470<//Time>
<rating>4</rating><Review>Lovely theater with beautifully restored art deco interior. Seating is comfy. Staff are typically friendly and helpful. The selection isn't huge (I think they have maybe 7 or 8 theaters, not super sure), but it usually has the current blockbusters and enough of a variety to suit my movie mood. There have only been a few occasions when I really wanted to see a specific movie that I couldn't find here. This remains my default theater and I really enjoy coming here.

I love that they do special series throughout the year. They had a classic movies series going on Wednesday nights for a few weeks for example, and I hope they keep the series events going. They also used to do a special talent show or trivia thing before movies in the big historic theater on popular nights, but I'm not sure if that is still happening.

It seems they will be slowly moving toward more sustainable practices, like reusable dishes similar to a restaurant rather than the disposable cups and packages typically found in the concessions, and I appreciate these future changes.

I've enjoyed this theater for years and will keep coming back regularly.<//Review><pictures>None< /pictures>< Response>

<date>1549061514080< /date>< rate>
5<//rate>
< Review>
A gem of Alameda, this movie theater is a community center for Alameda and shows a wide variety of movies appropriate for both kids and adults. There's a good restaurant called the Cinema Grill next-door which will serve you food in the theater if you want to have a meal and it's also a great place to go for drinks or dessert after a movie. Alameda Theatre is a beautifully restored Art Deco movie palace that's fun just to be in let alone watch a movie in. The city paid to restore it and they were smart enough to also pay for parking garage that's right around the corner so it's easy to park on most evenings.< /Review>

A great theater, particularly the main screen. In addition to wide release movies, they do a lot of classic movies and community events. Concessions stand prices are about the same as any other theater, not unreasonable, and they have beer. I live in Oakland, but I will make a trip to see movies here whenever I can.</Text>

5</rate>
< Text>
small, cozy theater in Alameda! one of our gems :) The staff are always the sweetest and have the best service. I love the $5.50 Tuesday deals, I like to go every Tuesday to check out movies until I've watched all the ones I wanted to! Plus sometimes there are special month offers where they offer free/even cheaper screenings! In the summers for example they hold kid friendly screenings of different movies throughout the month and it's such a great place to bring your family for a nice outing! plus they have a parking structure adjacent so you never have to worry about finding parking. it's also close to park street where all the eateries are! a cute local date spot if anything :)</Text>

< Text>
Alameda theater is a great place to go. Take your family or go by yourself or friends. It's always a good experience, the historical theater room is so beautiful! it's so big very comfortable, just a pleasant place to come and watch a movie. The popcorn is always fresh, they have a restaurant where you can order food in the theater and they will bring it to you, it's very nice, it's family-friendly, it's just fun! Everybody's so pleasant and sweet and kind I've never had an issue ever and I've been going there for quite a few years.
Tonight there was a issue with the sound, they stopped the movie and said they would refund your money if you wanted to leave right then, or you can watch the rest of the movie and get two tickets to return to the theatre.
My grandson and I decided to stay and watch the movie.Very nice, enjoyable, so yeah if you want a place to come where it's comfortable and nice come to Alameda theater you will not be disappointed< /Text>

<Rate>5<//Rate>< Text>
This historic theater and attach Cineplex is filled with rich history in Alameda. The main theater was built in 1932 and was active for about 50 years before closing down. It was restored and reopened in 2008 with the attached Cineplex. It was in the Guinness Book of World Records for the brightest projector. I'm not sure if it's still there or not. Highly recommended location to view a movie.<//Text>

<Gmap_id>0x808f86be0f8c89dd:0x7b58c36ce6683445</Gmap_id><Time>1505059856005< /Time><text>What a great, local, historic theater! I'm here almost weekly. The small theaters aren't bad and I wish the upstairs concessions were open, but that's not enough for a deduction and the main theater adds value. A local cosplay artist sets up some really cool scenes for some of the new releases in the lobby. You can rent the mezzanine for events, too. This place has some great vibes.

If your feature is in the main auditorium, then you're in for a treat. It's a huge screen, great sound, comfy seats, and some extra entertainment on Friday and Saturday (Alameda's Got Talent). During the NBA Finals, they telecast the Warriors games for a really fun watch parties. There's a mezzanine that I've yet to use, but that's on my list of things to do.

As for concessions, this is where I really like this theater. First, they've teamed up with the neighboring restaurant. You can get a special front row seat and they'll deliver your food to you in the theater! They also have pizza, beer, and wine. And for my kiddo, they have a $5 combo with popcorn, a small soda, and a fun sized pack of M&Ms.</text><UserId.>110618131638463984111<//UserId.><Rating>5< /Rating></record>

< Review>
A good movie house with 1 large historic theater and many smaller cineplex style theaters that show all the latest films. The theater had fallen into disrepair, but was purchased by a city/private partnership and restored to its former glory. Comfy seats. Good consessions. Decent matinee pricing.< /Review>

< Review>
Theatre #1 has the ornate decorations on it's walls and the original movie house, the other theatres were all added on later.  One of the movies we watched I noticed were slightly blurry and out of focus at the beginning as the titles were just less than tack sharp. The slightly off focus visual was it's weak spot.< /Review>

< review>
Great theater not owned by a big chain. Their historic theater is designed like a vintage theater with a stage in front of the screen. They okay current movies & have begun to upgrade their concessions so you can now by pizza, wraps, beer & wine along with your standard stuff. My only knock against them would be that you can't buy tickets online through Fandango. You can through the their site, but it's just gives you a slip that you have to get scanned at the box office or one of their kiosks to print your tickets.<//review>

1488572966849<//date>
< Rate>
5</Rate>
< text>
Part of the old school Theatre Revival movement, as seen in many cities, Alameda Theatre, as part of a new model, actually based on an old model, of customer service, and fun theater experiences, that go beyond to just coming and watching a movie. This lovingly restored theater both some of the nicest interior of any theater in United States, and is noted in the Guinness Book of World Records, as having the brightest theater projector in the world. Also, it is a nice break from the often overcrowded Emeryville, and Berkeley Theater scene. It is also a center for Community Affairs, where they have a talent night comma and often hold dramatic presentation to a place, poetry, music, and other performances there. A really nice place overall, and a nice combination of modern and classical theater elements.< /text>

<Gmap_id>0x808f86be0f8c89dd:0x7b58c36ce6683445< /Gmap_id><review>This independent cinema shows first run movies in the historic theater (completely restored and decorated) and the newly constructed cineplex (hiding behind the historic theater so it doesn't ruin the magnificent facade). The historic theater has a balcony, too.  In addition to the usual popcorn and such, after 5 p.m. you can order beer and wine.

One unique feature is that you can order food and drinks from the grill next door, and have it delivered to your seat during the movie. While there is a more limited menu than at the grill itself, it's still a decent selection.

Friday and Saturday nights, the historic theater hosts "Alameda's Got Talent" prior to the main feature. The theater also hosts special events, such as two New Year's Eve parties (one more family-oriented and alcohol free, the other with a no-host bar).< /review>< time>
1451079861443<//time>

<name>Kyle Wolfe< /name><text>I go here very frequently because it's the best theatre in terms of technical quality, but the service here is terrible. I've been forced to have to leave without buying tickets multiple times because one of my friends in a large group doesn't have an ID with their date of birth. If you are under 18, you cannot buy R tickets for other people without ID and are very strict about checking for it. I've had friends who have been turned away with their college student picture ID because it didn't specify a date of birth. If you bring a large group, expect to be asked for everyone to show ID, make sure everyone had their DOB listed. If one person doesn't have valid ID, you will not be able to buy a ticket for them. They are also very strict about bringing outside food and drinks in. I use to bring soda in my jacket but now they will check you at the entrance and confiscate any outside food and beverages. While the candy and drinks aren't reasonably priced, the popcorn is. You can get 50¬¢ refills which is very nice. Just know that if you get up to get a refill and try to come back into the theatre, the attendant will stop you and ask to see your ticket. <Resp>None<//Resp><text>I always enjoy going to the Alameda theatre. Parking can be difficult at times although there is a parking structure on the side, street parking and a parking lot directly across the street..since it is right off of the main shopping area it can get tight at peak times.
The theatre itself is really nice, staff are friendly, it is very clean & they show current movies. They also have fun retro nights where they play retro movies, a moms club for moms with small babies, talent shows ( can't remember when or how often) and general fun stuff going on to bring in the community. Lastly, they have a deal worked out with the adjoining restaurant so you can order food to your seat in the movie. No more settling for popcorn and a hot dog when you csn order sliders, fries, a salad..you name it. Its a fun theatre!<//text>< user_id>

I love so much about the Alameda Theater - the building, the movie choices, the bathrooms!

But . . .  we had to walk out of a movie today because the sound was TOO LOUD.  First the advertisements before the movie were loud, shrill and harsh, and then the movie The Hitman's Bodyguard was deafening any time the pace picked up.  My friend and I were not the only ones to walk out.  With headaches.

Alameda Theater:  Please turn down the volume.<//text>

< username>
Vera D.<//username>
< date>
1372120597075< /date>
<Rating>5< /Rating>< Review>
I LOVE the Alameda Theatre. You get super friendly service from the moment you walk in? The theatre itself is beautiful if you're an art deco fan, with its opulent gold gilded trim, floral swirls and grand staircases flanking the lobby. Until they got an espresso machine, they'd let you bring in Peet's coffee -- pretty flexible! The last two times I've been there, we've gotten to see Steve perform magic tricks before the previews started -- very entertaining and a personal touch. There was a problem with the projector tonight, but other than that it's always seemed to go smoothly. By the way, I've never paid for parking to see a movie here, but then they don't charge after 5pm....</Review>

<user_name>Guy Stevens</user_name><pics>None< /pics>< review>
After the city of Alameda GAVE the owner of this theatre over 10 million dollars of our tax money, and 10 years of tax free business. The theatre buys the very expensive and bad resteraunt next door again with city tax payer money and a guarantee of tax free business operation. In order to get a half way good seat (alibit one with food from the resteraunt spilled all over it that hasn't been cleaned in years) you have to buy absurdly expensive food from the resteraunt.

Save your money, wait for the movie to come out on DVD sit at home in clean seats and watch the movie in comfort. Maybe the city council learn something going forward and stops giving hard earned tax dollars to private business repeatedly.</review>

<Rating>4< /Rating><Date>1434261919608</Date><Pictures>None</Pictures><Text>Love the classic look and feel of this old-timey theater! The staff are really awesome, and the prices are very fair. $11 per adult tickets, $6.50 for a large popcorn. Not bad... You can also pre order tickets online, especially for high demand movies. Be aware though, this isn't like tge modern theaters that blast A/C like they are recreating the ice age. Theater might get warm, especially for a packed auditorium.

The location is perfect for grabbing dinner and then dessert at the many boba or froyo establishments in walking distance! Parking us also really easy around here too!< /Text><response>None<//response><user_id>110288469148184652948</user_id>< username>

< UserId.>
107879564876088728481< /UserId.>
< Name>
Anne Cronin< /Name>
< date>
1385947457778< /date>
<rate>5< /rate>< Text>
I remember working at this theater snack bar before it closed in the late 70's. It used to be like a center island in the middle of the lobby. The balconies were accessible for the one big original screen. The seats up there were suspiciouly nasty back in the day. I remember old Al, the old usher guy. The theater manager at the time was a guy named Pedderson. I think he kinda hated life and wasn't very nice. I later heard the guy died from a heart attack

The old screen curtains were ratty and full of soda and food stains. The hidden upper balcony store rooms where the snack bar supplies were stored were dark and dank. Probably the walls leaked as early as that if not before. Kinda spooky. I'm just glad I never spotted any rats or roaches.

Back then the giant "Alameda" neon sign outside was broken and never lit up. The marquee bulbs on the underside of the entrance overhang were always mostly burned out. The old box office was a small booth outside in the center of the front walk under the marquee overhang.

The old Ryders Diner and then later the Record Factory Store used to be where the new added multiplex screens and bistro/bar are now on the corner. I like the new theater now. It should've always remaind a theater. Too bad it never had a great Mighty Wurlitzer organ like the Oakland Paramount. That would've been cool.

It wasn't exactly the most ideal job. My fondest memory was being able to see the first Star Wars movie for free as many times I wanted. A lot of free movies and old Al looked the other way. Crappy job but good times. My first real job.</Text>

None<//Pictures>
